ning.\n\nActually, I'm realizing I can leverage the `POST /_nodes/reload_secure_settings` API to reload keystore entries without restarting the pods. If I create the secret, exec into each pod to add the keystore entries, then call that reload endpoint, I can avoid a full restart altogether. This is cleaner than the init container approach and gets the job done faster.\n\nBut for a proper disaster recovery drill, I should probably set up the persistent approach with an init container so the keystore entries survive pod restarts. Let me structure this in two phases: first get it working with the exec approach, then update the StatefulSet for persistence.\n\nI'll start by creating the secret with the S3 credentials, then patch the StatefulSet to add the init container that populates the keystore.\n\nWriting the StatefulSet patch... Writing the patch YAML... I'm thinking through how a strategic merge patch will handle the volumeMounts and volumes arrays. Since both containers and volumeMounts use `name` as their merge key, the new volumeMounts should be added to the existing ones without conflicts, and the new volumes will similarly merge with the existing config, certs, and data volumes.\n\nThe keystore file mount shouldn't be a problem either—I can mount it as a subPath in the same config directory alongside the existing elasticsearch.yml subPath mount, since each subPath creates a separate bind mount.\n\nThe main question is whether Elasticsearch will just load the pre-populated keystore we're providing or try to recreate it. Based on how Elasticsearch works, it checks if the keystore exists at startup and loads it if present, so providing one via the volume mount should work fine.\n\nNow I'm thinking through the actual implementation steps: create the secret, patch the StatefulSet to trigger a rolling restart, wait for the pods to stabilize, then register the snapshot repository and create the snapshot. For the StatefulSet patch, I'll write it to a temporary file a